// wf_embed WIT world — v0.1.0.
//
// Substrate-side text-embedding capability. Provides a single host
// callback that maps `(text, model)` to a dense f32 sentence
// embedding. The wf_sagegraph guest (memo §06 text-attributed feature
// mode) is the first planned consumer; future guests that need
// sentence embeddings for retrieval, clustering, or attribute
// vectorization can import the same interface without waiting for
// a per-model wasi:nn composition.
//
// # Why a host callback, not a wasm-composed fastembed?
//
// `~/git/fastembed-wasm/fastembed-component` builds a cdylib that
// imports `wasi:nn/{tensor,graph,inference,errors}@0.2.0-rc-2024-10-28`
// and depends on a caller-supplied ONNX file + tokenizer state on the
// component's filesystem. Composing it into `wf_sagegraph_nn` via
// `wasm-tools compose` is the "purer" WIT path but hits three real
// walls in one session:
//
//   * cargo-component + wasm-tools compose build-graph plumbing to
//     link two cdylibs (guest + fastembed) into one deployable
//     component,
//   * bundling the tokenizer.json + ONNX file into the composed
//     component's WASI filesystem preopens on every substrate
//     engine, and
//   * making the model-download story reproducible across CI hosts.
//
// The host-callback path (this WIT) is the substrate's already-
// established pattern for expensive native capabilities — see
// `wf:fulltext/host@0.1.0` (Manticore HTTP), `wf:document/host@1.3.0`
// (Sirix HTTP), `wf:sagegraph/host@0.2.0` (execute-query +
// http-post-json). One WIT interface, N engine registrations, one
// implementation per engine. The `wf_sagegraph` guest imports it in
// its text-attributed feature mode; every other guest that never
// touches it sees no change.
//
// # Determinism
//
// The interface is model-parameterised so the same input text +
// model name yields the same vector across substrate engines. The
// v0.1 substrate landing uses a deterministic SHA-256-derived stub
// projection (byte-stable, no model download, matches the wf_sagegraph
// v0.2 hash-of-model_url pattern); the follow-up production landing
// swaps in `fastembed-rs` behind the same signature.

package wf:embed@0.1.0;

/// The single interface substrate engines register. Kept package-
/// scoped so guest-side imports resolve as
/// `wf:embed/host@0.1.0` verbatim.
interface host {
    /// Encode `text` under the sentence-embedding model named
    /// `model` and return the dense vector. Byte-stable per
    /// (text, model, substrate version): every substrate engine
    /// that registers this interface uses the same deterministic
    /// implementation, so cross-engine parity holds for text-
    /// attributed features (memo §06).
    ///
    /// Recognised model names (v0.1):
    ///   * `bge-small-en`         — 384-dim (default when unknown)
    ///   * `all-MiniLM-L6-v2`     — 384-dim
    ///   * `bge-base-en`          — 768-dim
    ///   * `nomic-embed-text`     — 768-dim
    ///   * `bge-large-en`         — 1024-dim
    ///
    /// Unknown model names default to 384-dim and are surfaced as
    /// `Ok(_)` (the guest can still get a byte-stable vector for
    /// its own use — the substrate doesn't gate on the model
    /// catalog). Empty `text` returns
    /// `Err("embed-text: text is empty")`.
    embed-text: func(text: string, model: string) -> result<list<f32>, string>;

    /// List the model names the substrate registration recognises.
    /// Guests that want to negotiate can call this before
    /// `embed-text`; guests that hardcode a model name don't need
    /// it. Same list across every substrate engine.
    list-models: func() -> list<string>;
}

/// Placeholder world for the guest side. Consumers (wf_sagegraph in
/// text mode, future text-retrieval guests) import `host` from this
/// package. The guest world is not exported here — this crate's role
/// is only to own the shared WIT so both substrate engines and future
/// guests reference identical bytes.
world wf-embed {
    import host;
}
